{{for|the Denjoy–Luzin theorem about functions of bounded variation|Denjoy–Luzin–Saks theorem}}

In [[mathematics]], the '''Denjoy–Luzin theorem''', introduced independently by {{harvs|txt|last=Denjoy|authorlink=A. Denjoy|year=1912}} and  {{harvs|txt|last=Luzin|authorlink=N. N. Luzin|year=1912}} 
states that if a [[trigonometric series]] converges absolutely on a set of positive measure, then the sum of its [[coefficients]] converges absolutely, and in particular the trigonometric series converges absolutely everywhere.

