{{Infobox animal | name = F. D. C. Willard | image = | caption = F. D. C. Willard, a [[Siamese cat]], squinting astutely at the camera | othername = Felix Domesticus, Chester. | species = [[Cat]] | breed = [[Siamese cat]] | gender = Male | birth_date = 1968 | death_date = 1982 | known_for = First cat to co-author a physics paper | owner = Jack H. Hetherington }}
'''F. D. C. Willard''' (ca. 1968&ndash;1982) was the pen name of a [[Siamese cat]] named Chester, who internationally published under this name on [[physics]] in scientific journals, once as a [[co-author]] and another time as the sole author.
==Background== The [[United States|American]] physicist and mathematician Jack H. Hetherington, of [[Michigan State University]], in 1975 wanted to publish some of his research results in the field of low–temperature physics in the scientific journal ''[[Physical Review|Physical Review Letters]]''. A colleague, to whom he had given his paper for review, pointed out that Hetherington had used the [[Nosism|first person plural]] in his text, and that the journal would reject this form on submissions with a sole author. Rather than take the time to retype the article to use the singular form, or to bring in a co-author, Hetherington decided to invent one.<ref name=Zankl>{{cite|author=Heinrich Zankl|chapter=Einsteins preußischer Schatten und Hetheringtons Kater [Einstein's Prussian shadow and Hetherington's cat]|language=German|editors=Von Dunkelbirnen und Leuchtkaninchen|title=Erlebnis Wissenschaft|publisher=WILEY-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co.|location=Weinheim|year=2008|isbn=978-3-527-32114-8|chapter-url=http://www.wiley-vch.de/books/sample/3527321144_c01.pdf|pages=14–15}}</ref>
==Publications== [[image:FDC Willard - lapa.svg|thumb|upright=0.7|F. D. C. Willard's Signature]] Hetherington had a Siamese cat named Chester, who had been sired by a Siamese named Willard. Fearing that colleagues might recognize his pet's name, he thought it better to use the pet's initial. Aware that most Americans have at least two given names, he invented two more given names based on the [[scientific name]] for a [[house cat]], ''Felis domesticus'', and abbreviated them accordingly as F. D. C. His article, entitled "Two-, Three-, and Four-Atom Exchange Effects in bcc ³He" and written by J. H. Hetherington and F. D. C. Willard, was accepted by the Physical Review and published in number 35 (November 1975).<ref>{{cite|authors=J. H. Hetherington and F. D. C. Willard|title=Two-, Three-, and Four-Atom Exchange Effects in bcc ³He|url=http://prl.aps.org/abstract/PRL/v35/i21/p1442_1|journal=Physical Review Letters|volume=35|page=1442–1444|year=1975|bibcode=1975PhRvL..35.1442H|doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.35.1442}}</ref><ref name=AO>[http://www.atlasobscura.com/articles/in-1975-a-cat-coauthored-a-physics-paper Grundhauser, Eric. ''In 1975, a Cat Co-Authored a Physics Paper'' (Atlas Obscura; 30 August 2016)]</ref>
At the 15th International Conference on Low Temperature Physics in 1978 in [[Grenoble]], Hetherington's co-author was exposed: Hetherington had sent some signed copies of his article to friends and colleagues and included the "signature" (paw prints) of his co-author in them.<ref>{{cite book|author=R.L. Weber|title=More Random Walks in Science|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YrbanNOQ-bcC|date=1 January 1982|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-0-85498-040-6|pages=110–111}}</ref> Later, another essay appeared, this time solely authored by F. D. C. Willard, entitled "L'hélium 3 solide. Un antiferromagnétique nucléaire", published (in French) in September 1980 in the French popular science magazine ''[[La Recherche]]''.<ref>{{cite|authors=F. D. C. Willard|title=L’hélium 3 solide. Un antiferromagnétique nucléaire|journal=La Recherche|volume=114|year=1980}}</ref><ref name=AO/> Subsequently, Willard disappeared as an author from the professional world.
==Reception== The unmasking of Hetherington's co-author on the ''Physical Review'' essay, which was frequently referenced,<ref>{{cite|author=Beispiel|title=Journal of the Physical Society of Japan}}</ref> caused the co-authorship to become world-famous. The story goes that when inquiries were made to Hetherington's office at Michigan State University, and Hetherington was absent, the callers would ask to speak to the co-author instead.<ref>{{cite|url=http://www.academiaobscura.com/academic-animals|title=Academia Obscura, Academic Animals}}</ref> F. D. C. Willard appeared henceforth repeatedly in footnotes, where he was thanked for "useful contributions to the discussion" or oral communications,<ref name=Zankl/> and even offered a position as a professor.<ref>[http://www.academiaobscura.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/WoodruffLetter.pdf ''Woodruff Letter''] (from MSU Dean Truman O. Woodruff to Professor Jack Hetherington, dated 26 November 1975)</ref> F. D. C. Willard is sometimes included in lists of "Famous Cats" or "Historical Cats". As an [[April Fool's]] joke, in 2014 the American Physical Society announced that cat-authored papers, including the Hetherington/Willard paper, would henceforth be open-access (papers of the APS usually require subscription or membership for web access).<ref>{{cite|url=http://journals.aps.org/2014/04/01/aps-announces-a-new-open-access-initiative|title=APS Announces New Open Access Initiative}}</ref>
