{{Infobox scientist | name = Louis Leithold | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1924|11|16}} | birth_place = [[San Francisco]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|2005|4|29|1924|11|16}} | death_place = [[Los Angeles]] | residence = United States | citizenship = | nationality = American | fields = [[mathematics]] ([[calculus]]) | workplaces = [[Malibu High School]] | alma_mater = | doctoral_advisor = | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = ''[[The Calculus]]'' | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | influences = | influenced = [[Jaime Escalante]] | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | footnotes = | spouse = }}
'''Louis Leithold''' ([[San Francisco]], United States, 16 November 1924 – [[Los Angeles]], 29 April 2005) was an American [[mathematician]] and [[teacher]]. He is best known for authoring ''[[The Calculus]]'', a classic [[textbook]] about [[calculus]] that changed the teaching methods for calculus in world [[high school]]s and [[university|universities]].<ref name=britannica>{{cite web|title=Louis Leithold |work=Britannica Book of the Year, 2006|url= http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/1089492/Louis-Leithold|accessdate=6 February 2011 }}</ref> Known as "a legend in AP calculus circles," Leithold was the mentor of [[Jaime Escalante]], the Los Angeles high-school teacher whose story is the subject of the 1988 movie ''[[Stand and Deliver]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Louis Leithold, 80: Legendary calculus teacher wrote widely used textbook|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/834843101.html?dids=834843101:834843101&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=May+09%2C+2005&author=Los+Angeles+Times&pub=Chicago+Tribune&desc=LOUIS+LEITHOLD%2C+80+%3B+Legendary+calculus+teacher+wrote+widely+used+textbook&pqatl=google|accessdate=7 February 2011|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=9 May 2005}}</ref>
==Biography==
Leithold attained master's and doctorate degrees from the [[University of California, Berkeley]]. He went on to teach at [[Phoenix College]] (Arizona)<ref name=britannica/> (which has a math scholarship in his name<ref>{{cite news|title=Graduates with Honors|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Kk8iAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3qwFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5710,1642236&dq=louis-leithold&hl=en|accessdate=7 February 2011|newspaper=[[Argus-Press]]|date=20 May 1980}}</ref>), [[California State University, Los Angeles]], the [[University of Southern California]], [[Pepperdine University]], and [[The Open University]] (UK).<ref name=ap>{{cite news|last=Associated Press|title=Louis Leithold, an Innovator in the Teaching of Calculus, Dies at 80|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/05/10/national/10leithold.html?_r=2|accessdate=7 February 2011|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=10 May 2005}}</ref> In 1968, Leithold published ''The Calculus'', a "blockbuster best-seller" which simplified the teaching of calculus.<ref name=npr>{{cite news|last=Siegel|first=Robert|title=Late Author, Teacher Demystified Calculus for Thousands|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4645383|accessdate=7 February 2011|newspaper=[[NPR]]|date=9 May 2005}}</ref>
At age 72, after his retirement<ref name=ap/> from Pepperdine,<ref name=malibu/> he began teaching calculus at [[Malibu High School]], in [[Malibu, California]], drilling his students for the [[Advanced Placement Calculus]], and achieving considerable success.<ref name=ap/> He regularly assigned two hours of homework per night, and had two training sessions at his own house that ran Saturdays or Sundays from 9AM to 4PM before the AP test.<ref name=touch>{{cite news|last=Woo|first=Elaine|title=His Math Text Was the Standard, His Touch in Class Exceptional|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/may/08/local/me-leithold8|accessdate=8 February 2011|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=8 May 2005}}</ref> His teaching methods were praised for their liveliness, and his love for the topic was well known.<ref name=npr/> He also taught workshops for calculus teachers.<ref name=touch/><ref name=woo>{{cite news|last=Woo|first=Elaine|title=Obituaries: Fitting Tribute to Math Teacher; Late instructor Louis Leithold's students receive top scores on AP calculus exam|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/897946231.html?dids=897946231:897946231&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Sep+18%2C+2005&author=Elaine+Woo&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Obituaries%3B+Fitting+Tribute+to+Math+Teacher%3B+Late+instructor+Louis+Leithold%27s+students+receive+top+scores+on+AP+calculus+exam.&pqatl=google|accessdate=7 February 2011|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=18 September 2005}}</ref> One of the people he influenced was Jaime Escalante, who taught math to minority students at [[Garfield High School (Los Angeles County, California)|Garfield High School]] in [[East Los Angeles, California|East Los Angeles]]. Escalante's subsequent success as a teacher is portrayed in the 1988 film ''Stand and Deliver''.<ref name=ap/>
Leithold died of natural causes the week before his class (which he had been "relentlessly drilling" for eight months<ref name=ap/>) was to take the AP exam;<ref name=ap/> his students went on to receive top scores.<ref name=woo/> A memorial service was held in [[Glendale, California|Glendale]], and a scholarship established in his name.<ref name=malibu>{{cite news|title=News Briefs|url=http://www.malibutimes.com/articles/2005/05/11/news/newsbriefs.txt|accessdate=7 February 2011|newspaper=[[The Malibu Times]]|date=11 May 2005}}</ref>
