{{lowercase|title=mcrypt}}
'''mcrypt''' is a replacement for the popular [[Unix]] [[Crypt (Unix)|crypt]] command. crypt was a file encryption tool that used an [[algorithm]] very close to the [[World War II]] [[Enigma machine|Enigma]] cipher. Mcrypt provides the same functionality but uses several modern algorithms such as [[Advanced Encryption Standard|AES]]. Libmcrypt, Mcrypt's companion, is a library of code which contains the actual encryption functions and provides an easy method for use. The last update to libmcrypt was in 2007,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sourceforge.net/projects/mcrypt/files/Libmcrypt/|title=Libmcrypt releases}}</ref> despite years of unmerged patches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sourceforge.net/p/mcrypt/patches|title=Libmcrypt patches}}</ref> These facts have led security experts to declare mcrypt [[abandonware]] and discourage its use in new development. Prefer [[ccrypt]], [[libressl]], and others. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://paragonie.com/blog/2015/05/if-you-re-typing-word-mcrypt-into-your-code-you-re-doing-it-wrong|title= If You're Typing the Word MCRYPT Into Your PHP Code, You're Doing It Wrong|author=Paragon Initiative Enterprises}}</ref>
Examples of mcrypt usage in a Linux command line environment:<source lang=bash> mcrypt --list # See available encryption algorithms. mcrypt -a blowfish myfilename # Encrypts myfilename to myfilename.nc # using the Blowfish encryption algorithm. # You are prompted two times for a passphrase. mcrypt -d mytextfile.txt.nc # Decrypts mytextfile.txt.nc to mytextfile.txt. mcrypt -V -d -a enigma -o scrypt --bare # Can en/decrypt files crypted with SunOS crypt. mcrypt --help</source>
It implements numerous [[cryptography|cryptographic]] algorithms, mostly [[block cipher]]s and [[stream cipher]]s, some of which falls under [[export of cryptography|export restriction]]s in the [[United States]]. Algorithms include [[Data Encryption Standard|DES]], [[blowfish (cipher)|Blowfish]], [[RC4|ARCFOUR]], [[enigma machine|Enigma]], [[GOST (block cipher)|GOST]], [[LOKI97]], [[RC2]], [[Serpent (cipher)|Serpent]], Threeway, [[Twofish]], [[WAKE (cipher)|WAKE]], and [[XTEA]].
